# terraform-rhcs-rosa-hcp — Terraform & ROSA HCP

This repository implements **ROSA with Hosted Control Plane (HCP)** only. Do not mix **ROSA Classic** patterns, resources, or variables from `terraform-rhcs-rosa-classic`.

## Architecture

- **HCP**: Control plane in Red Hat’s AWS account; worker nodes in the customer account; connectivity via PrivateLink. Comparison table: [AWS — ROSA architecture models](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/rosa/latest/userguide/rosa-architecture-models.html#rosa-architecture-differences).
- **Provider source of truth**: [`terraform-redhat/rhcs`](https://github.com/terraform-redhat/terraform-provider-rhcs) — use registry schema/docs; do not invent attributes.

## Model separation (guardrails)

- Scope changes to **this repo** when editing here. Do not suggest Classic-only resources (e.g. `rhcs_cluster_rosa_classic`, non-HCP machine pools) in this codebase.
- Shared submodules (e.g. `modules/idp`) may still differ by architecture — follow **this** repo’s `main.tf` and `versions.tf`.

## Provider & version constraints

- **Root `versions.tf`** must list the **minimum compatible** `terraform-redhat/rhcs` and `hashicorp/aws` versions for the **entire module tree** (root + all `modules/**`). Terraform merges provider constraints across the configuration; **root constraints must not be lower than any submodule’s declared floor** — if any submodule needs a higher floor, **raise the root constraint**.
- Before adding an **AWS** resource or data source, confirm it exists in the **AWS provider version range** declared in `versions.tf`.
- If a feature needs a **minimum OpenShift version**, document it in the variable `description` and README when relevant.

## Submodules: AWS-only vs `rhcs`

- Some submodules declare **only** `hashicorp/aws` (and sometimes `time`, `random`, etc.) — no `terraform-redhat/rhcs`. They are still part of **this HCP** module; **do not** introduce resources or patterns that apply **only** to **ROSA Classic** (not HCP).
- **Do not** add `rhcs` resources to a submodule that is intentionally AWS-only unless the change truly requires the RHCS provider; follow that submodule’s existing `main.tf` and `versions.tf`.
- **AWS** resources and data sources must be supported by the **AWS** provider version range in **root** and that submodule’s `versions.tf` (same floor policy as **Provider & version constraints**).
- Adding or bumping **`required_providers`** in a submodule must stay consistent across the **module tree** — root `versions.tf` must reflect minimum compatible versions for providers used anywhere in the tree.

## Security

- Do not hardcode secrets or long-lived AWS keys in Terraform. Align with existing **`examples/`** and Red Hat guidance for STS, OIDC, and IRSA. Use **`sensitive`** where appropriate; avoid exposing secrets in outputs, state-adjacent logging, or ad-hoc debug prints.
- **Outputs:** If a submodule output is **`sensitive = true`**, any **root** (or parent) output that passes it through (e.g. **`value = module.child.output_name`**) must also use **`sensitive = true`**. Terraform requires this when the value is or derives from sensitive data; keep child and parent aligned (e.g. **`cluster_admin_username`** alongside **`cluster_admin_password`**).

## Variables

- Every variable: `type`, `description`, and `default` when optional — match tone and structure of existing `variables.tf`.
- Use **`snake_case`** for names (Terraform convention). Prefer **validation** / **lifecycle precondition** for simple checks (null/empty/enum); let the provider enforce complex cross-field rules.
- **Nullable values in `validation` conditions:** Do not pass a possibly-**`null`** expression into **`contains(...)`** (or similar functions that reject null). That can surface as **`Invalid value for "value" parameter: argument must not be null.`** during validation/plan. Use a **short-circuiting ternary** so `contains` runs only when the value is non-null, e.g. `var.example == null ? true : contains(["a", "b"], var.example)` — not `var.example == null || contains(..., var.example)`.
- **Import-safe `count` / `for_each`:** Avoid boolean **`count`** / **`for_each`** conditions that depend **only** on a **resource or data source attribute** that can be **`null`** in partial state (e.g. immediately after **`terraform import`** before refresh). Terraform requires **`true` or `false`**; **`null`** triggers **`The condition value is null. Conditions must either be true or false.`** Prefer driving **`count` / `for_each` from `var.*`** only. 
- **Typed maps vs `map(any)`:** When a map’s values are the same logical object (e.g. keyed log forwarders, pools), prefer **`map(object({ ... }))`** with **`optional(...)`** for nullable blocks — not **`map(any)`** — so mixed entries (e.g. one key uses `s3`, another `cloudwatch`) type-check without “all map elements must have the same type”. Add root **`validation`** blocks for cross-field rules users hit early; child modules may keep **`lifecycle` precondition** as a second line of defense.

